<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-130-182 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 045 042</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  June 13 1991 n1265 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The time bomb at your feet. (under the spotless floor of acomputer room lies potential disaster: environmental hazardsthreaten system functioning) (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Simpson, Alan K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Environmental hazards including dust, humidity, temperaturefluctuations, and rust, now account for more than 50 percent ofall computer system problems, and that figure is expected to riseto 75 percent by 1995.andP;  A common cause for disk crashes,particularly where thin-film head technology is involved, isconcrete dust that rises from improperly sealed subfloors and iscarried into the computer room by the air conditioning system.andO;Other culprits can be rust on floor jacks and elsewhere,temperature or humidity that fluctuates, and carbon dust producedby printers.andP;  A whole new specialty, that of the industryenvironmentalist, has arisen from the need to diagnose and dealwith such problems.andP;  While firms such as the UK-based HardwareEnvironmental Protection Agency can quickly detect theenvironmental causes of system failures, the consensus is that awiser approach is to schedule regular environmental audits,catching potential problems before they result in downtime.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TroubleshootingTutorialDiagnosticsFailureDown TimeAutomationComputer industryComputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Environmental hazards. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>